('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:exam:929b7f6a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q1", "question": "<p>Tick <strong>one</strong> box to identify which ERL function takes a single character and returns its character code.</p>", "options": ["ASC(char)", "CHR(code) — this instead converts a code number back into the character it represents, which is the opposite operation", "char.length", "char.upper"], "hint": "ASC goes from character → code. CHR goes the opposite way, from code → character."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul><li><strong>ASC(char)</strong></li></ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "ASC(char)."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:exam:40c80671', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "<p>name = \"Home\" . Tick <strong>one</strong> box to identify the value returned by  <strong>name.length</strong> .</p>", "options": ["4", "3", "5", "H, because .length is sometimes wrongly assumed to return the first character of the string rather than a count"], "hint": "Count every character in \"Home\", including all four letters."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul><li><strong>4</strong> (\"Home\" has 4 characters)</li></ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "4."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:exam:bfa59ee3', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q8", "question": "<p>The following code runs.</p><pre>name = \"abc\"\nname.upper\nprint(name)</pre><p>Tick <strong>one</strong> box for what is printed.</p>", "options": ["abc", "ABC", "Error — a string method''s return value must always be stored in a variable before the program can carry on running", "AbC"], "hint": ".upper returns a new string — it doesn''t change name unless the result is stored back into it."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul><li><strong>abc</strong> (unchanged — the result of .upper was never stored back into name)</li></ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "abc."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:02a10c12', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "For  name = \"Home\" , what does  name.length  return?", "options": ["4", "3", "5", "H, because .length is sometimes wrongly assumed to return the first character of the string rather than a count"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\"Home\" has 4 characters (H, o, m, e), so name.length returns 4."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:8a5f50f7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "For  name = \"Computer\" , what does  name.substring(0, 3)  return?", "options": ["Com", "Comp", "omp", "Compute, because the second argument is sometimes wrongly read as the index where the whole rest of the string should stop"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Starting at index 0 and taking 3 characters gives \"C\", \"o\", \"m\" — so \"Com\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:46d9685c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "For  name = \"Computer\" , what does  name.substring(3, 5)  return?", "options": ["puter", "Comp", "uter", "Compute, because the second argument is sometimes wrongly treated as an end position rather than a length"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Starting at index 3 and taking 5 characters covers indices 3–7: \"p\", \"u\", \"t\", \"e\", \"r\" — giving \"puter\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:e6b36039', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which ERL expression gives the LAST 4 characters of the string  code ?", "options": ["code.right(4)", "code.left(4)", "code.substring(4, code.length)", "code.upper, since converting to upper case is sometimes wrongly thought to be the only safe way to reach a string''s final characters"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "right(n) returns the last n characters. left(n) would instead give the FIRST 4."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:5880473a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is  ASC(\"Z\") ?", "options": ["90", "26", "122", "65, since that is the code for A and every capital letter is sometimes wrongly assumed to share the same code"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Z is the code 90 (A = 65, so Z = 65 + 25 = 90) — not the same as Z''s position in the alphabet, which is 26."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:2bf10801', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What does  CHR(97)  return?", "options": ["a", "A", "z", "97, since CHR is sometimes wrongly assumed to simply return the number it was given back unchanged"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "97 is the character code for lower-case \"a\". (65 is \"A\"; lower case starts 32 codes after upper case.)"}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:55884210', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is  ASC(\"0\") ?", "options": ["48", "0", "49", "zero, since ASC is sometimes wrongly assumed to return a character''s name rather than its numeric code"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The digit character \"0\" has the character code 48 — not the integer value 0."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:34e48ec7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "s1 = \"Green\"  and  s2 = \"house\" . What does  print(s1 + s2)  output?", "options": ["Greenhouse", "Green house, because the plus operator is sometimes wrongly assumed to automatically insert a space between two strings", "houseGreen", "GREENHOUSE"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "+ concatenates with nothing extra added: \"Green\" + \"house\" = \"Greenhouse\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:b7f84ce6', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What does  CHR(ASC(\"m\") + 1)  return?", "options": ["n", "M", "l", "N, since CHR is sometimes wrongly assumed to always return an upper-case letter regardless of the case of the original character"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "ASC(\"m\") = 109. 109 + 1 = 110, and CHR(110) is \"n\" — the next letter after m."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:ab59e9b6', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "s = \"Robot\" . What does  print(s.left(2) + s.right(2))  output?", "options": ["Root", "RoBot", "obot", "Robot, because concatenating the start and end of a string is sometimes wrongly assumed to just return the original string unchanged"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "s.left(2) = \"Ro\". s.right(2) = \"ot\" (the last 2 characters of \"Robot\"). Concatenating gives \"Ro\" + \"ot\" = \"Root\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:82b0272b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which index does the FIRST character of any ERL string have?", "options": ["0", "1", "-1", "The string''s length, since indexing is sometimes wrongly assumed to start counting from the end of a string"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "ERL strings are 0-indexed, so the first character is always at index 0."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:mcq:4c66abbe', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "s = \"Silver\" . What does  s.substring(2, 3)  return?", "options": ["lve", "Sil", "ilv", "ver, because the second argument is sometimes wrongly treated as the index where extraction should stop rather than a length"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Starting at index 2 and taking 3 characters covers indices 2, 3 and 4: \"l\", \"v\", \"e\" — giving \"lve\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tf:116fe528', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "str.substring(startIndex, numberOfChars) begins counting characters from index 0."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — ERL strings are 0-indexed, so index 0 is the first character."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tf:83b62785', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The second value passed into substring tells the computer which index to stop at."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The second value is a COUNT of characters to take (a length), not an index to stop at."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tf:fa559baf', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "str.left(3) and str.right(3) always return the same characters, for any string."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "left(n) takes characters from the START of the string; right(n) takes them from the END. For most strings these give different results."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tf:a23f5c89', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "ASC(\"a\") returns a different value from ASC(\"A\")."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — lower-case and capital letters have different character codes: ASC(\"a\") is 97, ASC(\"A\") is 65."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tf:c2c22d4b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "CHR is the opposite operation to ASC."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — ASC converts a character to its code; CHR converts a code back to its character. CHR(ASC(x)) always gives back x."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tf:893642e2', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Concatenating two strings with + automatically inserts a space between them."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "+ joins strings exactly as they are, with nothing extra added — any space needed must be included in the strings being joined."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tf:eae0a858', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "\"Cat\".upper returns \"CAT\"."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — .upper converts every letter in the string to upper case."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tf:7851c5fd', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "str.length counts spaces as characters too."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — .length counts every character in the string, including spaces and punctuation, not just letters."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:learn:8c56b60b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Strings as a list of characters", "reading": "<h4>Every character has a position</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>OCR''s Exam Reference Language treats a string as an ordered list of characters, each with a position called its <strong>index</strong>. Indexing starts at <strong>0</strong> — the first character is at index 0, not index 1.</li>\n<li><code>str.length</code> returns the <strong>number of characters</strong> in a string — this includes spaces and punctuation, not just letters.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">word = \"Pencil\"\nprint(word.length)      // 6\n\n// index:   0    1    2    3    4    5\n// char:    P    e    n    c    i    l</div>\n<ul>\n<li>Knowing the index of each character is the foundation for every other string operation on this page — you will use it constantly with <code>substring</code>, <code>left</code> and <code>right</code>.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A string is stored as  city = \"Leeds\" . What index does the letter L sit at?", "options": ["0", "1", "5, because that is the total number of characters city contains in total", "The letter L does not have an index, because only whole strings can be indexed, never individual characters"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "ERL strings are 0-indexed, so the very first character — here, L — is always at index 0."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:learn:46d9685c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "substring(startIndex, numberOfChars) — the length trap", "reading": "<h4>The single most common string mistake</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><code>str.substring(startIndex, numberOfChars)</code> extracts part of a string. <strong>startIndex</strong> is where to begin (0-indexed). <strong>numberOfChars</strong> is <strong>how many characters to take</strong> from that point — it is a <strong>length</strong>, <strong>NOT</strong> the index where extraction should stop.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">name = \"Computer\"\nprint(name.substring(0, 3))   // \"Com\"    — start at index 0, take 3 characters\nprint(name.substring(3, 5))   // \"puter\"  — start at index 3, take 5 characters</div>\n<ul>\n<li>Many students wrongly read the second value as an end position (the way some other languages work). In ERL it never is — always count forwards <strong>from</strong> the start index for however many characters are asked for.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "For  name = \"Computer\" , what does  name.substring(3, 5)  return?", "options": ["puter", "Comp", "ute", "Computer, because the second argument is sometimes wrongly read as meaning ''return everything from here to the end''"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Starting at index 3 and taking 5 characters covers indices 3, 4, 5, 6 and 7 — \"p\", \"u\", \"t\", \"e\", \"r\" — giving \"puter\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:learn:30a75441', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "left(n) and right(n) — quick ends", "reading": "<h4>Shortcuts for the start and end of a string</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><code>str.left(n)</code> — returns the first <strong>n</strong> characters of the string.</li>\n<li><code>str.right(n)</code> — returns the last <strong>n</strong> characters of the string.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">word = \"Keyboard\"\nprint(word.left(3))     // \"Key\"\nprint(word.right(4))    // \"oard\"</div>\n<ul>\n<li>Both could be written using <code>substring</code> instead — <code>word.left(3)</code> is the same as <code>word.substring(0, 3)</code> — but <code>left</code> and <code>right</code> are quicker to write when you only need one end of the string.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What does  word.right(4)  return, for  word = \"Notebook\" ?", "options": ["book", "Note", "The first four characters, because right(n) is sometimes wrongly assumed to count n characters in from the very start", "ebook"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "right(n) takes the LAST n characters. \"Notebook\" has 8 characters, so the last 4 are \"book\". left(4) would instead give \"Note\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:learn:8018e486', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "upper and lower — changing case", "reading": "<h4>Converting between capital and lower-case letters</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><code>str.upper</code> — returns the string converted to <strong>UPPER CASE</strong>.</li>\n<li><code>str.lower</code> — returns the string converted to <strong>lower case</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">shout = \"Warning\"\nprint(shout.upper)     // \"WARNING\"\nprint(shout.lower)     // \"warning\"</div>\n<ul>\n<li>Like every string operation on this page, <code>upper</code> and <code>lower</code> <strong>return a new string</strong> — they do <strong>not</strong> change the original variable. If you want to keep the result, you must store it: <code>shout = shout.upper</code>.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "s = \"team\"  is set, then the line  s.upper  runs on its own (its result is not stored anywhere). What is  s  afterwards?", "options": ["\"team\" — unchanged, because .upper returns a new string rather than changing the original variable", "\"TEAM\"", "\"Team\", with only the first letter capitalised as a compromise", "An error, because a string method''s result must always be stored in a variable before the program can continue"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "String methods like .upper return a NEW string; they don''t modify the original variable. Since the result here isn''t stored anywhere, s stays \"team\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:learn:8e5d855c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "ASC and CHR — characters and codes", "reading": "<h4>Converting between a character and its code</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Every character a computer stores has a numeric <strong>character code</strong> (its position in the character set, e.g. ASCII).</li>\n<li><code>ASC(char)</code> — takes a single character and returns its <strong>character code</strong> (a number).</li>\n<li><code>CHR(code)</code> — takes a code (a number) and returns the <strong>character</strong> it represents. CHR is the opposite of ASC.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">print(ASC(\"A\"))     // 65\nprint(CHR(65))      // \"A\"\nprint(ASC(\"a\"))     // 97\nprint(CHR(97))      // \"a\"</div>\n<ul>\n<li>ASC and CHR always undo each other: <code>CHR(ASC(letter))</code> always gives back <code>letter</code> unchanged.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What does  CHR(65)  return?", "options": ["A", "65", "a", "ASC(65), since CHR is sometimes wrongly assumed to need combining with ASC before it can return anything at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "CHR(code) converts a code number into its character. 65 is the character code for the capital letter A."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:learn:cda772cf', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "ASCII blocks — the four anchor points", "reading": "<h4>You don''t need the whole table — just four anchors</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Capital letters, lower-case letters and digits each sit in their own <strong>consecutive block</strong> of character codes. For GCSE, you should know four anchor points:</li>\n<li><code>ASC(\"A\") = 65</code>  and  <code>ASC(\"Z\") = 90</code></li>\n<li><code>ASC(\"a\") = 97</code>  and  <code>ASC(\"0\") = 48</code></li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">// Because each block is consecutive, adding 1 to a code moves to the NEXT character:\nletter = \"B\"\nnextLetter = CHR(ASC(letter) + 1)\nprint(nextLetter)          // \"C\"</div>\n<ul>\n<li>This \"add to the code, then convert back\" pattern is the basis of exam questions that ask you to shift a letter forwards or backwards through the alphabet.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Using the anchor points  ASC(\"A\") = 65  and  ASC(\"a\") = 97 , what is  ASC(\"b\") ?", "options": ["98", "66, since capital and lower-case letters are sometimes wrongly assumed to always share exactly the same code", "97", "2, because b is sometimes wrongly assumed to give its position in the alphabet rather than its character code"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Lower-case letters run consecutively from a = 97, so b (the next letter) is 97 + 1 = 98."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:learn:f9aab967', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Concatenation", "reading": "<h4>Joining strings end to end</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Concatenation</strong> joins strings together using <code>+</code>. The strings are joined exactly as they are — <strong>nothing extra is added</strong>, so include any spaces or punctuation yourself.</li>\n<li>Both sides of <code>+</code> must be strings — joining a string with a number usually needs the number converted first (see casting in 2.2.2).</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">first = \"Hello\"\nsecond = \"World\"\nmessage = first + \" \" + second\nprint(message)          // \"Hello World\"\nprint(message.length)   // 11</div>\n<ul>\n<li>Forgetting the <code>\" \"</code> in the middle is a common slip — <code>first + second</code> alone would give <code>\"HelloWorld\"</code> with no space at all.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "s1 = \"Data\" and s2 = \"base\" . What does  print(s1 + s2)  output?", "options": ["Database", "Data base, with a single space automatically inserted between the two words by the plus operator", "base Data", "DataBase"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "+ joins the strings with nothing extra added. \"Data\" + \"base\" gives \"Database\" — no space is inserted automatically."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:learn:c7b47b6f', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Combining string operations", "reading": "<h4>Building up a result from several small steps</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Exam questions often chain two or three string operations together. Work out each step <strong>separately</strong>, in the order they happen, before combining the results.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">first = \"Amara\"\nlast = \"Diallo\"\ninitials = first.left(1) + last.left(1)\nprint(initials.upper)      // \"AD\"</div>\n<ul>\n<li>Step by step: <code>first.left(1)</code> is <code>\"A\"</code>; <code>last.left(1)</code> is <code>\"D\"</code>; concatenating gives <code>\"AD\"</code>; then <code>.upper</code> is applied to the <strong>whole</strong> result — which is already upper case here, so it makes no visible difference.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "s = \"Bridge\" . What does  s.substring(1, 3).upper  return?", "options": ["RID", "BRI, since .upper is sometimes wrongly assumed to apply only to the very first character extracted by substring", "rid", "ridge"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "substring(1, 3) takes 3 characters from index 1: \"r\", \"i\", \"d\" → \"rid\". .upper is then applied to that whole result, giving \"RID\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:learn:8ac8b6b5', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Tracing \"what does this output?\" questions", "reading": "<h4>Working through combined string code, one line at a time</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The safest way to answer a string-tracing question is <strong>slow and mechanical</strong>: work out the value of each line in order, substituting the current value of any variable as you reach it — exactly like tracing any other code.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">s = \"Journey\"\na = s.substring(0, 4)     // a = \"Jour\"\nb = s.right(3)             // b = \"ney\"\nresult = a.upper + b       // result = \"JOUR\" + \"ney\"\nprint(result)               // \"JOURney\"</div>\n<ul>\n<li>Notice that <code>.upper</code> only applies to <code>a</code>, not to <code>b</code> — each variable keeps whatever case it had until an operation is applied to it directly.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "s = \"Garden\" ,  a = s.left(3) ,  b = s.right(3).upper . What does  print(a + b)  output?", "options": ["GarDEN", "GARDEN, because concatenating two parts of the same string always converts the whole result to upper case", "gardEN", "garden"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "a = s.left(3) = \"Gar\" (unchanged case). b = s.right(3).upper = \"DEN\" (upper-cased). a + b = \"Gar\" + \"DEN\" = \"GarDEN\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:learn:60d24ffd', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Common exam patterns", "reading": "<h4>String tasks that come up again and again</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Check the first or last character</strong>: <code>str.left(1)</code> or <code>str.right(1)</code> — useful for checking a currency symbol, or whether a filename ends in a particular letter.</li>\n<li><strong>Check the length before extracting</strong>: it''s good practice to check <code>str.length</code> is big enough before calling <code>substring</code>, so the program doesn''t try to take more characters than the string actually has.</li>\n<li><strong>Pull out a file extension</strong>: for a filename like <code>\"photo.jpg\"</code>, <code>str.right(3)</code> gives <code>\"jpg\"</code> — as long as you already know the extension is 3 characters long.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">filename = \"report.pdf\"\nextension = filename.right(3)\nprint(extension)          // \"pdf\"</div>\n<ul>\n<li>These aren''t new ERL commands — they''re just <code>substring</code>, <code>left</code>, <code>right</code> and <code>length</code> applied to a realistic problem, which is exactly how they appear in exam questions.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A program needs to check whether the string  code  starts with the letter \"A\". Which expression tests this correctly?", "options": ["code.left(1) == \"A\"", "code.right(1) == \"A\", since right(1) is sometimes wrongly assumed to return the very first character of a string", "code.length == \"A\"", "code.upper == \"A\""]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "code.left(1) returns the first character. Comparing it to \"A\" checks whether the string starts with A. right(1) would instead check the LAST character."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:misc:a4f0061e', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking the second value in substring(start, n) is the index where extraction stops.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The second value is a <strong>length</strong> — how many characters to take — not an end index. For <code>s.substring(2, 4)</code>, the extraction takes <strong>4 characters</strong> starting at index 2 (indices 2, 3, 4 and 5), not everything up to index 4.</p>", "question": "For  s = \"Elephant\" , what does  s.substring(1, 3)  return?", "options": ["lep, because it starts at index 1 and takes 3 characters (indices 1, 2 and 3)", "le, because it starts at index 1 and stops just before index 3", "Ele, since the first argument is sometimes wrongly read as ''from the start, up to this many characters''", "hant, since substring is sometimes wrongly assumed to count backward from the end of the string by default"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "substring(1, 3) starts at index 1 and takes 3 characters: indices 1, 2, 3 are \"l\", \"e\", \"p\" — giving \"lep\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:misc:1569ebc7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Mixing up left(n) and right(n) — using one when the other is needed.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> <strong>left(n)</strong> counts from the <strong>start</strong> of the string. <strong>right(n)</strong> counts from the <strong>end</strong>. A quick way to remember: reading left to right, <code>left</code> is what you meet <strong>first</strong>.</p>", "question": "A filename is stored as  file = \"holiday.png\" . Which expression correctly returns the file extension  \"png\" ?", "options": ["file.right(3)", "file.left(3), since left(n) is sometimes wrongly assumed to count characters in from whichever end is needed for the task", "file.length", "file.upper"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The extension sits at the END of the filename, so right(3) is needed. left(3) would instead give \"hol\", the first 3 characters."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:misc:56e013a3', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking ASC(letter) returns the letter''s position in the alphabet (e.g. ASC(\"Z\") = 26).</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> ASC returns the character''s numeric <strong>code</strong> in the character set (e.g. ASCII), which is <strong>not</strong> the same as its position in the alphabet. <code>ASC(\"Z\") = 90</code>, even though Z is the 26th letter.</p>", "question": "What is  ASC(\"C\") ?", "options": ["67", "3, since C is the third letter of the alphabet and ASC is sometimes wrongly assumed to return this alphabet position", "99", "68"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "ASC(\"C\") returns C''s character code, 67 (A = 65, B = 66, C = 67) — not its alphabet position, 3."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:misc:100ab04b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking concatenation with + automatically inserts a space, or converts a number to a string automatically.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> <code>+</code> joins strings <strong>exactly as they are</strong> — you must add any spaces yourself, using <code>\" \"</code>. Joining a string with a number often needs the number <strong>converted to a string first</strong>, or the program may cause an error.</p>", "question": "name = \"Sam\"  and  age = 12 . Which line correctly prints  \"Sam is 12\" ?", "options": ["print(name + \" is \" + str(age))", "print(name + \" is \" + age), since + is sometimes wrongly assumed to join a string and a number without needing any conversion", "print(name + is + age)", "print(name age)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Concatenation needs both sides to be strings, so the number age must be converted first — here using str(age) — with the space added explicitly."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:misc:627d7c01', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking .upper or .lower permanently changes the original string in place.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> <code>str.upper</code> and <code>str.lower</code> each <strong>return a new string</strong> — they do <strong>not</strong> change the variable they were called on. To keep the result, you must store it back: <code>str = str.upper</code>.</p>", "question": "word = \"Cabin\"  is set, then  word.upper  runs on its own (its result is not stored anywhere). What does  print(word)  show straight after?", "options": ["Cabin, unchanged, because .upper returns a new string rather than modifying word itself", "CABIN", "cabin", "An error, because .upper must always be assigned to a variable before the program can carry on running"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": ".upper returns a NEW string; it doesn''t modify word. Since the result wasn''t stored anywhere, word is still \"Cabin\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:misc:dc4a19a2', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking string indexing starts at 1, the way people usually count things.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> ERL strings are <strong>0-indexed</strong>, exactly like arrays: the first character is always at index <strong>0</strong>. For <code>word = \"Cat\"</code>, the valid indices are <code>0, 1, 2</code> — there is no index 3.</p>", "question": "word = \"Frog\"  (4 characters). Which of these is NOT a valid index into this string?", "options": ["4", "0", "2", "3, because the last valid index of a 4-character string is sometimes wrongly assumed to always equal its length minus one, giving 3"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A 4-character string has indices 0, 1, 2 and 3 (0-indexed) — index 4 does not exist, since the last valid index is always one less than the string''s length."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tips:8807abdf', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Tracing combined string operations carefully", "reading": "<p>\"What does this output?\" questions on strings are worth a lot of marks, and the safest approach is <strong>slow and mechanical</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Work out each string method <strong>separately</strong>, in the order the lines run — don''t try to do several steps in your head at once.</li>\n<li>For <code>substring</code>, write out the indices involved first, if it helps, before working out the characters.</li>\n<li>Remember <code>substring(start, len)</code> — the second value is <strong>how many</strong> characters, not where to stop.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong> for <code>s = \"Window\"</code>, <code>a = s.substring(0, 4)</code>, <code>b = s.right(2).upper</code>, <code>print(a + b)</code>: work out <code>a</code> first (\"Wind\"), then <code>b</code> (\"ow\" → \"OW\"), then combine: \"Wind\" + \"OW\" = \"WindOW\". Slow beats clever.</p>", "question": "What is the safest way to answer a ''what does this string code output?'' question?", "options": ["Work through it mechanically, one operation at a time, writing down each new value as it changes", "Read the code once quickly and write down whichever answer looks the most likely based on the variable names used", "Only check the very last line of the code, since earlier lines rarely affect what actually gets printed at the end", "Count how many string methods are used, since the output length usually matches that number"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Working through the code mechanically — one operation at a time — is reliable. Guessing from names or skipping lines is not."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tips:47dc8cdf', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — The substring(start, len) trap", "reading": "<p>The single most repeated string mistake at GCSE is misreading the second argument of <code>substring</code>. Fix it with one rule:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>startIndex</strong> — where to begin (0-indexed).</li>\n<li><strong>numberOfChars</strong> — how MANY characters to take from there. It is a count, never an end position.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Worked example:</strong> for <code>s = \"Marathon\"</code>, <code>s.substring(2, 3)</code> starts at index 2 and takes 3 characters: indices 2, 3, 4 are \"r\", \"a\", \"t\" — giving \"rat\", <strong>not</strong> \"ratho\" (which is what you''d get if you (incorrectly) treated 3 as an end index).</p>", "question": "For  s = \"Marathon\" , what does  s.substring(2, 3)  correctly return?", "options": ["rat", "ara", "rathon, from treating 3 as the index the extraction should continue up to and including", "Mar"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Starting at index 2 and taking 3 characters gives indices 2, 3, 4: \"r\", \"a\", \"t\" — \"rat\"."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:tips:da64cacd', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — ASC/CHR shifting questions", "reading": "<p>Some questions ask you to shift a character forwards or backwards through the alphabet — for example a simple cipher. The pattern is always the same three steps:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Convert the character to its code with <code>ASC</code>.</li>\n<li>Add or subtract the shift amount.</li>\n<li>Convert the new code back to a character with <code>CHR</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong> shift <code>\"K\"</code> forward by 2 letters: <code>ASC(\"K\") = 75</code>; <code>75 + 2 = 77</code>; <code>CHR(77) = \"M\"</code>. Watch out for a shift that would push the code past <code>Z</code> (90) or <code>z</code> (122) — GCSE questions usually keep the shift small enough that this doesn''t happen.</p>", "question": "Using ASC and CHR, what letter do you get by shifting  \"F\"  forward by 3 places?", "options": ["I", "G, from adding only 1 instead of the full shift amount given in the question", "C, from subtracting the shift instead of adding it", "F3, from joining the letter and the shift amount together as if by concatenation"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "ASC(\"F\") = 70. 70 + 3 = 73. CHR(73) = \"I\" — the letter 3 places after F in the alphabet."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation:fib:a326274c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3a-string-manipulation', '2.2.3a String Manipulation', 'fib', 'fib', 1, '{"question": "A string''s characters are numbered starting from _____, not from 1.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["count", "65", "last", "0"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "0"}}'::jsonb),
