('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:learn:ef8d5f56', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Why use an array?", "reading": "<h4>Storing many related values under one name</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Without an array, storing five test scores would need five separate variables: <code>score1</code>, <code>score2</code>, <code>score3</code>, <code>score4</code>, <code>score5</code>.</li>\n<li>An <strong>array</strong> stores several values of the <strong>same type</strong> under a single name instead, e.g. <code>scores</code>. Each individual value is called an <strong>element</strong>.</li>\n<li>Because every element shares one name, a <strong>loop</strong> can process the whole array — adding the values up, searching through them, or printing each one — without writing a separate line of code for every value.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">// Without an array\nscore1 = 56\nscore2 = 78\nscore3 = 91\n\n// With an array\narray scores[3]\nscores[0] = 56\nscores[1] = 78\nscores[2] = 91</div>", "question": "What is the main advantage of using an array instead of several separate variables to store related data?", "options": ["A loop can process every value using one name and an index, instead of writing a separate line of code for each variable", "Arrays automatically sort their values into ascending order the moment any new element is assigned to them, no matter what", "An array can store values of several completely different data types mixed together within the very same single element", "Arrays always take up far less memory than an ordinary variable does, no matter how many elements they end up holding"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "An array''s real strength is that a loop can process every element using one name and an index — that''s what makes it worth using over separate variables."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:learn:846e238b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Declaring a 1D array — static and fixed size", "reading": "<h4>Reserving space for a fixed number of elements</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A 1D array is declared with a name and a <strong>size</strong> in square brackets, e.g. <code>array scores[5]</code> reserves space for 5 elements.</li>\n<li>ERL arrays are <strong>static</strong> — once declared, the size <strong>cannot change</strong>. You cannot add a 6th element to a 5-element array while the program is running.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">array scores[5]     // reserves 5 elements</div>\n<ul>\n<li>If a program does not know in advance exactly how many values it will need, the array must be declared big enough to hold the maximum possible number of values.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Why can''t a program add a 6th value to an array that was declared as  array scores[5] ?", "options": ["It can — ERL arrays automatically resize themselves whenever a new value is assigned beyond the declared size", "Arrays in ERL are static, so their size is fixed once declared and cannot grow", "Because scores is a reserved keyword, so no more than 5 values may ever be assigned to any array with that name", "Because 5 is the maximum size any array is allowed to be declared with in ERL, regardless of the array''s name"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "ERL arrays are static: the size is fixed at the point of declaration and cannot grow or shrink afterwards."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:learn:3be404fe', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "0-indexing — the first element is index 0", "reading": "<h4>Every array element has a numbered position</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Each element in an array has an <strong>index</strong> — its numbered position. ERL arrays are <strong>0-indexed</strong>: the <strong>first</strong> element is always at index <strong>0</strong>, not index 1.</li>\n<li>For <code>array scores[5]</code>, the valid indices are <code>0, 1, 2, 3, 4</code> — five elements, but the <strong>last</strong> index is <strong>4</strong>, not 5.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">array scores[5]\nscores[0] = 90\nscores[1] = 65\nscores[2] = 78\nprint(scores[2])    // 78</div>", "question": "array letters[7]  is declared. What is the index of the LAST element in this array?", "options": ["7, because that is the number used in the array''s declaration to state its size", "0, since 0-indexing means the very first element is also treated as the array''s last element", "6", "1, because the second element is sometimes miscounted as being the actual last index of a small array"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "A 7-element array holds indices 0 to 6 (0-indexed), so the last valid index is 6 — one less than the declared size of 7."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:learn:89d05a58', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Assigning and accessing elements", "reading": "<h4>Writing to, and reading from, an element</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>To <strong>assign</strong> a value to an element, write the array name with the index in square brackets on the left of an <code>=</code>: <code>scores[0] = 90</code>.</li>\n<li>To <strong>access</strong> (read) the value stored at an element, use the same square-bracket notation anywhere a value is needed — for example inside a <code>print</code> statement or a calculation.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">array ages[4]\nages[0] = 15\nages[1] = 16\nages[2] = 15\nages[3] = 17\nprint(ages[1])            // 16\ntotal = ages[0] + ages[2]\nprint(total)               // 30</div>", "question": "For the array ages[4] set up above (ages[0]=15, ages[1]=16, ages[2]=15, ages[3]=17), what does  print(ages[1] + ages[3])  output?", "options": ["31, because this instead adds together the two elements stored at index 0 and index 2, not index 1 and index 3", "15, since ages[1] and ages[3] are mistakenly treated as being exactly the same single element", "32, because this instead adds together the two elements stored at index 0 and index 3, not index 1 and index 3", "33"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "ages[1] is 16 and ages[3] is 17, so ages[1] + ages[3] = 16 + 17 = 33."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays:learn:dff57f61', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-2-3b-arrays', '2.2.3b Arrays', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Looping through a 1D array — totalling", "reading": "<h4>Using a for loop to process every element</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Because array indices run from 0 up to (size − 1), a <strong>for loop</strong> using a counter variable as the index can visit every element in turn.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">array prices[4]\nprices[0] = 12\nprices[1] = 25\nprices[2] = 8\nprices[3] = 19\ntotal = 0\nfor i = 0 to 3\n  total = total + prices[i]\nnext i\nprint(total)    // 64</div>\n<ul>\n<li>The loop runs from <code>i = 0</code> to <code>i = 3</code> — the <strong>last valid index</strong> of a 4-element array — not to 4.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "In the loop above, why does the for loop run  for i = 0 to 3  rather than  for i = 0 to 4 ?", "options": ["Because prices[4] has 4 elements, with valid indices 0 to 3 — index 4 does not exist", "Because a for loop is only ever able to repeat a maximum of 4 times in total, regardless of how big the array actually is", "Because the total variable would otherwise be calculated incorrectly, even though every index from 0 to 4 is genuinely valid", "Because ERL for loops always stop one iteration earlier than the number written after ''to'', on every single occasion"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "prices[4] holds 4 elements at indices 0, 1, 2 and 3 (0-indexed) — there is no prices[4], so the loop must stop at 3."}'::jsonb)
